  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions\n- Impose penalties and fines for violations\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Significant monetary fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential imprisonment\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Compliance with international anti-money laundering standards\n- Cooperation with global financial regulatory bodies\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the concealment of illegally obtained funds.",
